\end{tabular}
\caption{The compound statement $p \lor (\lnot p)$ is a tautology, and the compound statement $p \land (\lnot p)$ is a contradiction.}
\end{figure}

We refer to the tautology $p \lor (\lnot p)$ as the Law of the Excluded Middle.
\end{defn}

\begin{remark}[The Logical Rule of Inference] More generally, we say that a compound implication $P \implies Q$ is a tautology whenever the truth values of the constituent propositions make $P$ true (because, in this case, $Q$ is also true).
